00:06:53,637 --> 00:06:56,521
We'll come to exactly how he defines that later.

45
00:06:56,901 --> 00:07:02,730
Then he points to the second, which is the cause of dukkha, which, of course, lies in that craving.

46
00:07:03,672 --> 00:07:05,834
And the third is the cessation of dukkha.

47
00:07:06,435 --> 00:07:11,622
Dukkha is completely overcome by letting go of that craving and attachment.

48
00:07:12,845 --> 00:07:20,555
And then there's the path, of course, leading to the cessation of suffering, a cessation of dukkha, suffering, the Eightfold Path.

49
00:07:23,269 --> 00:07:28,096
And then he goes on to say what we should do about this dukkha.

50
00:07:28,857 --> 00:07:32,120
So this is the noble truth of suffering, dukkha.

51
00:07:32,240 --> 00:07:33,182
I'll use the word dukkha.

52
00:07:34,043 --> 00:07:37,247
The noble truth of suffering is to be fully understood.

53
00:07:38,048 --> 00:07:41,752
The noble truth of dukkha has been fully understood.

54
00:07:41,812 --> 00:07:43,675
So he's talking about himself now.

55
00:07:45,528 --> 00:07:49,192
Then he talks about the origin of dukkha.

56
00:07:49,632 --> 00:07:53,755
The noble truth of the origin of dukkha is to be abandoned.

57
00:07:54,817 --> 00:07:58,201
That cause of dukkha is eventually to be abandoned.

58
00:07:59,302 --> 00:08:04,206
And then he states of himself, the origin of dukkha has been abandoned.

59
00:08:06,189 --> 00:08:11,754
In the third one, he says there is a noble truth of the cessation, the complete eradication of dukkha.

60
00:08:12,545 --> 00:08:16,730
The noble truth of the sensation of dukkha is to be realized.

61
00:08:16,750 --> 00:08:20,437
So this is something that is to be personally experienced.

62
00:08:20,557 --> 00:08:22,740
That's the liberation from suffering.

63
00:08:23,540 --> 00:08:28,288
And the noble truth of dukkha has been realized by himself.

64
00:08:33,296 --> 00:08:36,380
This discourse was given to his five companions.

65
00:08:36,681 --> 00:08:38,062
